Buffer incoming bytes and track how much has been consumed:

```rust
let mut bytes = Vec::new();

while let Some(chunk) = stream.next().await {
    let chunk = chunk.context("Stream read error")?;
    bytes.extend_from_slice(&chunk);

    let text = String::from_utf8_lossy(&bytes);
    let mut consumed = 0;

    for line in text.lines() {
        consumed += line.len() + 1;  // +1 for newline

        if let Some(data) = line.strip_prefix("data: ") {
            // Process the SSE event data...
        }
    }

    // Only discard bytes we've fully processed
    bytes = bytes[consumed.min(bytes.len())..].to_vec();
}
```

The critical detail is `consumed.min(bytes.len())`. Without the `min`, you'd panic if `consumed` exceeds the buffer length (which can happen due to lossy UTF-8 conversion changing byte counts). The remaining bytes after truncation might be: (1) a partial line that hasn't received its newline yet, (2) partial UTF-8 bytes at the chunk boundary, or (3) nothing if the chunk ended on a line boundary. The next iteration will extend these bytes with the next chunk and try again.

This pattern works identically for both OpenAI (`data: {...}\ndata: [DONE]`) and Anthropic (`event: type\ndata: {...}`) SSE formats.

